Good Morning HSTS Family!
Due to an overwhelming access of Remote Learning across the state. Most platform servers such as Google Meet, Zoom and etc. are crashing, this is not due to an local issue.

We understand the frustration, we feel it as well. If your child can not login to their classroom, it's ok, we know this is not just a learning curve for HSTS but the entire state.

Please check your emails, the website and most importantly your phone calls and messages. Mr. Bell will sending calls home often with guidelines and updates on technical issues the state is having at this time.

If your having an email issue: email wenona.anstead@hstsedu.org, for a password reset, thank you.

Call 252-257-5853 for any questions and concerns.

WE ARE IN THIS TOGETHER!

post_text:
CHECK OUT HSTS's principal Mr. Bell, speaking on COVID-19 Remote Learning, social distancing and all about the great things here at The Haliwa-Saponi Tribal School. Mr. Bell was invited to do an interview with the Center For Energy Education, located in Roanoke Rapids, North Carolina. Our students have made several field trips to the campus and they loved it. We look forward to working with C4EE in the future.

https://youtu.be/A6FG0rMjmdg

What is C4EE?
The Center for Energy Education (C4EE) is a 501(c)3 nonprofit corporation and a center for renewable energy research, education, and workforce development for the eastern United States. The C4EE provides a place to raise awareness of renewable energy and its importance locally, regionally, and globally. The C4EE is a hub for the renewable energy industry, a hands-on training ground for solar installations, a destination for students and families to learn about renewable energy resources, and an education and training facility to provide the knowledge and skills needed to pursue a career in the growing renewable energy industry.

LEARNING BINDER NOTEBOOKS RETURNS AND RECEIVE!

All student work that was picked up last week is due back this Thursday, March 26, 2020. Parents please remember we are not expecting all your child(s) work back as we know a lot was given out.

What we do expect is at least 50% to 100% completion. There is more than ample enough time to complete assignments. Remember you have all your child(s) teachers contact information as well as the schools.

Drop off Completed work and Pick up new work: There will be drop off bins located in the cafeteria with your child(s) grade level on them. Place returning work in the bin and look on assigned table for their new work.

We know this is a difficult time for us all. Our main concern is you and your child(s) safety and the obvious.......OUR CHILDREN'S EDUCATION! WE CAN NOT LET THEIR AMAZING BECOME LAZY. READ! LEARN! STUDY! THRIVE!

shared_text:
REDCAP.WAKEHEALTH.EDU
AIMS Application

Suela Richardson is with Haliwa-Saponi Voice.
January 7, 2019 at 4:42 PM ·

I am very excited to announce that the application period for the 2019 American Indian BioMedical Science (AIMS) Summer Academy! The 2019 AIMS Academy will be held July 7-12, 2019, on the campuses of Wake Forest University and Wake Forest School of Medicine.
AIMS is open to American Indian High School students in Central/Eastern North Carolina who have an interest in health and biomedical science careers.
AIMS is free to all participants and transportation is provided.

There are 2 ways to apply: Online at https://is.gd/AIMSApp

Applications are due by March 4, 2019. The AIMS application process is competitive, but there is no minimum GPA. Letters regarding program acceptance will be mailed no later than April 1, 2019.

Students must self-identify as American Indian and be interested in a career in healthcare or biomedical science.

Please contact Mrs. Sarah Langdon (slangdon@wakehealth.edu) if you have any questions.
